%S A222010 0,1,3,7
%N A222010 Dimensions of spheres that admit continuous multiplications with unit element.
%C A222010 Adams's (1960) Hopf invariant one theorem states that S^0, S^1, S^3, S^7 are the only spheres that are H-spaces, i.e., that admit continuous multiplications with unit element.
%C A222010 This is related to the fact that nontrivial cross products only exist in vector spaces of 3 or 7 dimensions. [_Jonathan Vos Post_, Feb 09 2013]
%H A222010 J. F. Adams, <a href="https://www.maths.ed.ac.uk/~v1ranick/papers/adams1.pdf">On the non-existence of elements of Hopf invariant one</a>, Ann. Math., 72 (1960), 20-104.
%H A222010 Peter F. McLoughlin, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1212.3515">When does a cross product on R^{n} exist?</a>, arXiv:1212.3515 [math.HO], 2012-2013.
%H A222010 Wikipedia, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H-space">H-space</a>
%H A222010 Wikipedia, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hopf_invariant_one">Hopf invariant one</a>
%F A222010 a(n) = 2^n - 1 for n = 0, 1, 2, 3.
%F A222010 a(n) = A222011(n) - 1.
%e A222010 0, 1, 3, 7 are members because multiplications on S^0, S^1, S^3, S^7 are defined by regarding them as the unit spheres in the real, complex, quaternion, and Cayley numbers, respectively.
%Y A222010 Cf. A222011.
